What was already done ✅

  - Lazy loading — loading="lazy" on thumbnails
  - Sharp compression — WebP conversion at upload

  What's now implemented

  1. Serve images directly
  - New uploads write to apps/web/public/uploads/products/ — Next.js serves them directly, no proxy hop
  - Old images fall back through the existing rewrite to the API (backward compatible)
  - Removed localhost from remotePatterns (no longer needed for local images)
  - Configurable via UPLOADS_DIR env var for production deploys

  2. Blur placeholders
  - Upload route now generates a 10×10 WebP blur (~100–200 bytes) and returns it as a base64 blurDataUrl
  - blurDataUrl field added to ProductImage DB table (migration applied:
  20260508113553_add_blur_data_url)
  - placeholder="blur" + blurDataURL wired to every <Image> on the home page, product listing, and
  product detail gallery

  3. Preload critical images
  - Home page: first featured product card uses priority (emits <link rel="preload">)
  - Product listing: already had priority={index === 0} — added loading="lazy" for the rest for
  consistency
  - Product detail: already had priority on the main image

  4. Redis lazy caching
  - ioredis installed with lazy connect, offline queue disabled, 2s connect timeout — gracefully
  degrades if Redis isn't running
  - Product list (GET /api/products) and detail (GET /api/products/:slug) cached for 60s
  - Admin create/patch/delete invalidates all products:* keys immediately
  - Zero impact if Redis is down — falls back to direct DB

  ▎ One step needed: Stop the dev server and restart it (pnpm dev) — Windows won't let Prisma regenerate
  ▎  the client while the DLL is in use. The migration is already applied to the DB.